# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: subversion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The open source community has used Subversion widely: for example, in projects such as Apache Software Foundation, FreeBSD, SourceForge, and from 2006 to 2019, GCC.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] CodePlex was previously a common host for Subversion repositories.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Subversion was created by CollabNet Inc. in 2000, and was a top-level Apache project being built and used by a global community of contributors.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] CollabNet founded the Subversion project in 2000 as an effort to write an open-source version-control system which operated much like CVS but which fixed the bugs and supplied some features missing in CVS.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] By 2001, Subversion had advanced sufficiently to host its own source code, and in February 2004, version 1.0 was released.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] In November 2009, Subversion was accepted into Apache Incubator: this marked the beginning of the process to become a standard top-level Apache project.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] It became a top-level Apache project on February 17, 2010.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Release dates are extracted from Apache Subversion's `CHANGES` file, which records all release history.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Subversion offers two types of repository storage.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The original development of Subversion used the Berkeley DB package.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Subversion has some limitations with Berkeley DB usage when a program that accesses the database crashes or terminates forcibly.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] No data loss or corruption occurs, but the repository remains offline while Berkeley DB replays the journal and cleans up any outstanding locks.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The safest way to use Subversion with a Berkeley DB repository involves a single server-process running as one user (instead of through a shared filesystem).
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The Berkeley DB backend was deprecated in version 1.8.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] In 2004, a new storage subsystem was developed and named FSFS.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] It works faster than the Berkeley DB backend on directories with a large number of files and takes less disk space, due to less logging.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Beginning with Subversion 1.2, FSFS became the default data store for new repositories.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The etymology of "FSFS" is based on Subversion's use of the term "filesystem" for its repository storage system.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] FSFS stores its contents directly within the operating system's filesystem, rather than a structured system like Berkeley DB.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Thus, it is a "[Subversion] FileSystem atop the FileSystem".
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] A new filesystem, called FSX, is under development to remove some limitations of FSFS.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] It was added in version 1.9 and not considered production-ready.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] As of version 1.14, it is still marked as experimental.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] WebDAV/Delta-V (over http or https) using the mod_dav_svn module for Apache 2.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] This mode uses the http://host/path access scheme or https://host/path for secure connections using ssl.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Custom "svn" protocol (default port 3690), using plain text or over TCP/IP.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] This mode uses either the svn://host/path access scheme for unencrypted transport or svn+ssh://host/path scheme for tunneling over ssh.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] All three means can access both FSFS and Berkeley DB repositories.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Any 1.x version of a client can work with any 1.x server.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Newer clients and servers have additional features and performance capabilities, but have fallback support for older clients/servers.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Internally, a Subversion system comprises several libraries arranged as layers.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Each performs a specific task and allows developers to create their own tools at the desired level of complexity and specificity.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The lowest level; it implements the versioned filesystem which stores the user data.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Concerned with the repository built up around the filesystem.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] It has many helper functions and handles the various "hooks" that a repository may have, e.g., scripts that run when an action is performed.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Together, Fs and Repos constitute the "filesystem interface".
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Handles "repository access", both local and remote.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] From this point on, repositories are referred to using URLs, e.g.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] It abstracts repository access and provides common client tasks, such as authenticating users or comparing versions.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Subversion clients use the Wc library to manage the local working copy.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] One can view the Subversion filesystem as "two-dimensional".
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Each revision in a Subversion filesystem has its own *root*, which is used to access contents at that revision.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Files are stored as links to the most recent change; thus a Subversion repository is quite compact.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The system consumes storage space proportional to the number of changes made, not to the number of revisions.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The Subversion filesystem uses transactions to keep changes atomic.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] A transaction operates on a specified revision of the filesystem, not necessarily the latest.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The transaction has its own *root*, on which changes are made.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] It is then either committed and becomes the latest revision, or is aborted.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The transaction is actually a long-lived filesystem object; a client does not need to commit or abort a transaction itself, rather it can also begin a transaction, exit, and then can re-open the transaction and continue using it.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Potentially, multiple clients can access the same transaction and work together on an atomic change, though no existing clients expose this capability.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] One important feature of the Subversion filesystem is properties: simple *name*=*value* pairs of text.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Most properties occur on filesystem entries (i.e., files and directories).
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] These are versioned just like other changes to the filesystem.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The Subversion client reserves the 'svn:' prefix for built-in properties, but other names can be used to define custom properties.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Affects the handling of diffs and merging.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] A list of filename patterns to ignore in a directory.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] to substitute into a file when changes are made.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] This is used to maintain certain information (e.g., author, date of last change, revision number) in a file without human intervention.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Used when the working copy is needed with a specific EOL style.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] "native" is commonly used, so that EOLs match the user's OS EOL style.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Repositories may require this property on all files to prevent inconsistent line endings, which can cause a problem in itself.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Allows parts of other repositories to be automatically checked out into a subdirectory.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Specifies that a file is to be checked out with file permissions set to read-only.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] This is designed for use with the locking mechanism.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The read-only permission reminds one to obtain a lock before modifying the file: obtaining a lock makes the file writable, and releasing the lock makes it read-only again.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Locks are only enforced during a commit operation.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Locks can be used without setting this property.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] However, that is not recommended, because it introduces the risk of someone modifying a locked file; they will only discover it has been locked when their commit fails.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] This property is not meant to be set or modified directly by users.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] When a symbolic link is added to the repository, a file containing the link target is created with this property set.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] When a Unix-like system checks out this file, the client converts it to a symbolic link.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Used to track merge data (revision numbers) in Subversion 1.5 (or later).
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] command, and it is not recommended to change its value manually.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Subversion also uses properties on revisions themselves.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Like the above properties on filesystem entries, the names are completely arbitrary, with the Subversion client using certain properties prefixed with 'svn:'.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] However, these properties are not versioned, and they can be changed later if allowed by a pre-revprop-change hook.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The name of the user that submitted the change(s).
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The user-supplied description of the change(s).
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Subversion uses the inter-file branching model from Perforce to implement branches and tagging.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] A branch is a separate line of development.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Tagging refers to labeling the repository at a certain point in time so that it can be easily found in the future.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] In Subversion, the only difference between branches and tags is how they are used.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] A new branch or tag is set up by using the "svn copy" command, which should be used in place of the native operating system mechanism.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The copied directory is linked to the original in the repository to preserve its history, and the copy takes very little extra space in the repository.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] All the versions in each branch maintain the history of the file up to the point of the copy, plus any changes made since.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] One can "merge" changes back into the trunk or between branches.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] A known problem in Subversion affects the implementation of the file and directory rename operation.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] As of 2014, Subversion implements the renaming of files and directories as a "copy" to the new name followed by a "delete" of the old name.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Only the names change, all data relating to the edit history remains the same, and Subversion will still use the old name in older revisions of the "tree".
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] However, Subversion may become confused when a move conflicts with edits made elsewhere, both for regular commits and when merging branches.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The Subversion 1.5 release addressed some of these scenarios while others remained problematic.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The Subversion 1.8 release addressed some of these problems by making moves a first-class operation on the client, but it is still treated as copy+delete in the repository.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] As of 2013, Subversion lacks some repository-administration and management features.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] For instance, someone may wish to edit the repository to permanently remove all historical records of certain data.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Subversion does not have built-in support to achieve this simply.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Subversion stores additional copies of data on the local machine, which can become an issue with very large projects or files, or if developers work on multiple branches simultaneously.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] In versions prior to 1.7 these `.svn` directories on the client side could become corrupted by ill-advised user activity like global search/replace operations.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Starting with version 1.7 Subversion uses a single centralized .svn folder per working area.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Subversion does not store the modification times of files.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] As such, a file checked out of a Subversion repository will have the 'current' date (instead of the modification time in the repository), and a file checked into the repository will have the date of the check-in (instead of the modification time of the file being checked in).
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] This might not always be what is wanted.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] To mitigate this, third-party tools exist that allow for preserving modification time and other filesystem meta-data.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] However, giving checked out files a current date is important as well — this is how tools like make(1) will take notice of a changed file for rebuilding it.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Subversion uses a centralized revision control model.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Ben Collins-Sussman, one of the designers of Subversion, believes a centralised model would help prevent "insecure programmers" from hiding their work from other team members during development.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Some users of version control systems see the centralised model as detrimental; famously, Linus Torvalds attacked Subversion's model and its developers.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Subversion often does not deal well with the filename normalization performed by the HFS+ filesystem.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] This can cause problems when files with accented characters in their names are added to the repository on a non-HFS+ filesystem and the repository is then used with HFS+.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Revision numbers are difficult to remember in any version-control system.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] For this reason, most systems offer symbolic *tags* as user-friendly references to them.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Subversion does not have such a feature and what its documentation recommends to use instead is very different in nature.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Instead of implementing tags as *references* to points in history, Subversion recommends making snapshot *copies* into a well-known subdirectory ("`tags/`") in the space of the repository tree.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Only a few predefined *references* are available: `HEAD`, `BASE`, `PREV` and `COMMITTED`.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] When two (ideally independent) object types live in the repository tree, a "fight to the top" can ensue.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Tags, by their conventional definition, are both read-only and light-weight, on the repository and client.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Subversion copies are not read-only, and while they are light-weight on the repository, they are incredibly heavy-weight on the client.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] To address such issues, posters on the Subversion mailing lists have suggested a new feature called "labels" or "aliases".
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] SVN labels would more closely resemble the "tags" of other systems such as CVS or Git.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The fact that Subversion has global revision numbers opens the way to a very simple label → revision implementation.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Yet as of 2013, no progress has been made and symbolic tags are not in the list of the most wanted features.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] CollabNet has continued its involvement with Subversion, but the project runs as an independent open source community.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] In November 2009, the project was accepted into the Apache Incubator, aiming to become part of the Apache Software Foundation's efforts.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Since March 2010, the project is formally known as Apache Subversion, being a part of the Apache Top-Level Projects.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] In October 2009, WANdisco announced the hiring of core Subversion committers as the company moved to become a major corporate sponsor of the project.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] This included Hyrum Wright, president of the Subversion Corporation and release manager for the Subversion project since early 2008, who joined the company to lead its open source team.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The Subversion open-source community does not provide binaries, but potential users can download binaries from volunteers.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] While the Subversion project does not include an official graphical user interface (GUI) for use with Subversion, third parties have developed a number of different GUIs, along with a wide variety of additional ancillary software.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Work announced in 2009 included SubversionJ (a Java API) and implementation of the Obliterate command, similar to that provided by Perforce.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] Both of these enhancements were sponsored by WANdisco.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The Subversion committers normally have at least one or two new features under active development at any one time.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The 1.7 release of Subversion in October 2011 included a streamlined HTTP transport to improve performance and a rewritten working-copy library.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] In 2002, a design contest was held to select the logo for Subversion.
[src:subversion/apache-subversion] The original entries can be found here as well as the votes for each logo.
[src:subversion/page] Apache Subversion is fortunate to have a community that values documentation.
[src:subversion/page] This page contains pointers to varies sources of documentation aimed at Subversion users and developers both of Subversion and of third-party tools with which Subversion integrates.
[src:subversion/page] Much of this documentation is itself freely licensed, so if you spot errors in them, please feel free to submit corrections to the relevant owners of the documentation.
[src:subversion/page] If you want to know how to use Subversion, you can find a number of published user manuals available for purchase online.
[src:subversion/page] One of these texts — Version Control With Subversion (affectionately known as "the Subversion book") — carries a free license, was developed openly by the Subversion community itself, and is also available in full online for free at https://svnbook.red-bean.com.
[src:subversion/page] The Subversion community operates at peak efficiency when everyone honors the various policies which were established by the community as the result of years of experience.
[src:subversion/page] The following documents provide invaluable insight into How Stuff Gets Done Around Here.
[src:subversion/page] We hope you find them useful not only as you contribute to Subversion, but also as you then seek to develop and establish best practices in your own software projects.
[src:subversion/page] Subversion is a collection of modular libraries written in the C programming language, each of which has a clearly defined collection of functions and types that together make up Subversion's application programming interface (API).
[src:subversion/page] After Subversion versions have reached their end of life, we still provide the old documentation for archive/historical purposes.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] In version control systems, a **repository** is a data structure that stores metadata for a set of files or directory structure.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] Depending on whether the version control system in use is distributed, like Git or Mercurial, or centralized, like Subversion, CVS, or Perforce, the whole set of information in the repository may be duplicated on every user's system or may be maintained on a single server.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] Some of the metadata that a repository contains includes, among other things, a historical record of changes in the repository, a set of commit objects, and a set of references to commit objects, called *heads*.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] The main purpose of a repository is to store a set of files, as well as the history of changes made to those files.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] Exactly how each version control system handles storing those changes, however, differs greatly.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] For instance, Subversion in the past relied on a database instance but has since moved to storing its changes directly on the filesystem.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] These differences in storage techniques have generally led to diverse uses of version control by different groups, depending on their needs.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] In software engineering, a version control system is used to keep track of versions of a set of files, usually to allow multiple developers to collaborate on a project.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] The repository keeps track of the files in the project, which is represented as a graph.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] A distributed version control system is made up of central and branch repositories.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] A central repository exists on the server.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] To make changes to it, a developer first works on a branch repository, and proceeds to commit the change to the former.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] A code forge is a web interface to a version control system.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] A user can commonly browse repositories and their constituent files on the page itself.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] While forges are mainly used to perform version control operations, some forges allow users to host static web pages by uploading its source code (such as HTML and JavaScript, but not PHP) to a repository.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] This is usually done in order to provide documentation or a landing page for a software project.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] The use of repositories as a place to upload web documents allows version control to be integrated, and additionally allows quick iteration because changes are pushed through the Version Control System instead of having to upload the file through a protocol like FTP.
[src:subversion/repository-version-control] Examples of this kind of service include Codeberg Pages, GitHub Pages and GitLab Pages.
[src:subversion/svn-branchmerge] This documentation was written to describe the 1.7.x series of Apache™ Subversion®.
[src:subversion/svn-branchmerge] If you are running a different version of Subversion, you are strongly encouraged to visit http://www.svnbook.com/ and instead consult the version of this documentation appropriate for your version of Subversion.
[src:subversion/svn-branchmerge] Branching and merging are fundamental aspects of version control, simple enough to explain conceptually but offering just enough complexity and nuance to merit their own chapter in this book.
[src:subversion/svn-branchmerge] Herein, we'll introduce you to the general ideas behind these operations as well as Subversion's somewhat unique approach to them.
[src:subversion/svn-branchmerge] If you've not familiarized yourself with Subversion's basic concepts (found in Chapter 1, *Fundamental Concepts*), we recommmend that you do so before reading this chapter.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] Theory is useful, but its application is just plain fun.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] Let's move now into the details of using Subversion.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] By the time you reach the end of this chapter, you will be able to perform all the tasks you need to use Subversion in a normal day's work.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] You'll start with getting your files into Subversion, followed by an initial checkout of your code.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] We'll then walk you through making changes and examining those changes.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] You'll also see how to bring changes made by others into your working copy, examine them, and work through any conflicts that might arise.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] This chapter will not provide exhaustive coverage of all of Subversion's commands—rather, it's a conversational introduction to the most common Subversion tasks that you'll encounter.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] This chapter assumes that you've read and understood Chapter 1, *Fundamental Concepts* and are familiar with the general model of Subversion.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] For a complete reference of all commands, see Chapter 9, *Subversion Complete Reference*.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] Also, this chapter assumes that the reader is seeking information about how to interact in a basic fashion with an existing Subversion repository.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] No repository means no working copy; no working copy means not much of interest in this chapter.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] There are many Internet sites which offer free or inexpensive Subversion repository hosting services.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] Or, if you'd prefer to set up and administer your own repositories, check out Chapter 5, *Repository Administration*.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] But don't expect the examples in this chapter to work without the user having access to a Subversion repository.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] Finally, any Subversion operation that contacts the repository over a network may potentially require that the user authenticate.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] For the sake of simplicity, our examples throughout this chapter avoid demonstrating and discussing authentication.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] Be aware that if you hope to apply the knowledge herein to an existing, real-world Subversion instance, you'll probably be forced to provide at least a username and password to the server.
[src:subversion/svn-tour] See the section called “Client Credentials” for a detailed description of Subversion's handling of authentication and client credentials.
[src:subversion/version-control] Version control is a component of software configuration management.
[src:subversion/version-control] A **version control system** is a software tool that automates version control.
[src:subversion/version-control] Alternatively, version control is embedded as a feature of some systems such as word processors, spreadsheets, collaborative web docs, and content management systems, such as Wikipedia's page history.
[src:subversion/version-control] Version control includes options to view old versions and to revert a file to a previous version.
[src:subversion/version-control] As teams develop software, it is common to deploy multiple versions of the same software, and for different developers to work on one or more different versions simultaneously.
[src:subversion/version-control] Bugs or features of the software are often only present in certain versions (because of the fixing of some problems and the introduction of others as the program develops).
[src:subversion/version-control] Therefore, for the purposes of locating and fixing bugs, it is vitally important to be able to retrieve and run different versions of the software to determine in which version(s) the problem occurs.
[src:subversion/version-control] It may also be necessary to develop two versions of the software concurrently: for instance, where one version has bugs fixed, but no new features (branch), while the other version is where new features are worked on (trunk).
[src:subversion/version-control] At the simplest level, developers could simply retain multiple copies of the different versions of the program, and label them appropriately.
[src:subversion/version-control] This simple approach has been used in many large software projects.
[src:subversion/version-control] While this method can work, it is inefficient as many near-identical copies of the program have to be maintained.
[src:subversion/version-control] This requires a lot of self-discipline on the part of developers and often leads to mistakes.
[src:subversion/version-control] Since the code base is the same, it also requires granting read-write-execute permission to a set of developers, and this adds the pressure of someone managing permissions so that the code base is not compromised, which adds more complexity.
[src:subversion/version-control] Consequently, systems to automate some or all of the revision control process have been developed.
[src:subversion/version-control] This abstracts most operational steps (hides them from ordinary users).
[src:subversion/version-control] Moreover, in software development, legal and business practice, and other environments, it has become increasingly common for a single document or snippet of code to be edited by a team, the members of which may be geographically dispersed and may pursue different and even contrary interests.
[src:subversion/version-control] Sophisticated revision control that tracks and accounts for ownership of changes to documents and code may be extremely helpful or even indispensable in such situations.
[src:subversion/version-control] Revision control may also track changes to configuration files, such as those typically stored in `/etc` or `/usr/local/etc` on Unix systems.
[src:subversion/version-control] This gives system administrators another way to easily track changes made and a way to roll back to earlier versions should the need arise.
[src:subversion/version-control] Many version control systems identify the version of a file as a number or letter, called the *version number*, *version*, *revision number*, *revision*, or *revision level*.
[src:subversion/version-control] For example, the first version of a file might be version *1*.
[src:subversion/version-control] When the file is changed the next version is *2*.
[src:subversion/version-control] Each version is associated with a timestamp and the person making the change.
[src:subversion/version-control] Revisions can be compared, restored, and, with some types of files, merged.
[src:subversion/version-control] IBM's OS/360 IEBUPDTE software update tool dates back to 1962, arguably a precursor to version control system tools.
[src:subversion/version-control] Two source management and version control packages that were heavily used by IBM 360/370 installations were The Librarian and Panvalet.
[src:subversion/version-control] A full system designed for source code control was started in 1972: the Source Code Control System (SCCS), again for the OS/360.
[src:subversion/version-control] SCCS's user manual, especially the introduction, which was published on December 4, 1975, implied that it was the first deliberate revision control system.
[src:subversion/version-control] The Revision Control System (RCS) followed in 1982 and, later, Concurrent Versions System (CVS) added network and concurrent development features to RCS.
[src:subversion/version-control] After CVS, a dominant successor was Subversion, followed by the rise of distributed version control tools such as Git.
[src:subversion/version-control] Revision control manages changes to a set of data over time.
[src:subversion/version-control] These changes can be structured in various ways.
[src:subversion/version-control] Often the data is thought of as a collection of many individual items, such as files or documents, and changes to individual files are tracked.
[src:subversion/version-control] This is in line with the notion of keeping files separate but causes problems when identity changes, which happens when files are renamed, split or merged.
[src:subversion/version-control] Accordingly, some systems such as Git, consider changes to the data as a whole instead, which is less intuitive for simple changes but simplifies more complex changes.
[src:subversion/version-control] As a simple example, when editing a computer file, the data stored in memory by the editing program is the working copy, which is committed by saving the file.
[src:subversion/version-control] Concretely, one may print out a document, edit it by hand, and only later manually input the changes into a computer and save it.
[src:subversion/version-control] For source code control, the working copy is instead a copy of all files in a particular revision, generally stored locally on the developer's computer; in this case saving the file only changes the working copy, and checking into the repository is a separate step.
[src:subversion/version-control] If multiple people are working on a single data set or document, they are implicitly creating branches of the data (in their working copies), and thus issues of merging arise, as discussed below.
[src:subversion/version-control] For simple collaborative document editing, this can be prevented by using file locking or simply avoiding working on the same document that someone else is working on.
[src:subversion/version-control] Revision control systems are often centralized, with a single authoritative data store, the *repository,* and check-outs and check-ins done with reference to this central repository.
[src:subversion/version-control] Alternatively, in distributed revision control, no single repository is authoritative, and data can be checked out and checked into any repository.
[src:subversion/version-control] When checking into a different repository, this is interpreted as a merge or patch.
[src:subversion/version-control] In terms of graph theory, revisions are generally thought of as a line of development (the *trunk*) with branches off of this, forming a directed tree, visualized as one or more parallel lines of development (the "mainlines" of the branches) branching off a trunk.
[src:subversion/version-control] In reality the structure is more complicated, forming a directed acyclic graph, but for many purposes "tree with merges" is an adequate approximation.
[src:subversion/version-control] Revisions occur in sequence over time, and thus can be arranged in order, either by revision number or timestamp.
[src:subversion/version-control] Revisions are based on past revisions, though it is possible to largely or completely replace an earlier revision, such as "delete all existing text, insert new text".
[src:subversion/version-control] In the simplest case, with no branching or undoing, each revision is based on its immediate predecessor alone, and they form a simple line, with a single latest version, the "HEAD" revision or *tip*.
[src:subversion/version-control] In graph theory terms, drawing each revision as a point and each "derived revision" relationship as an arrow (conventionally pointing from older to newer, in the same direction as time), this is a linear graph.
[src:subversion/version-control] In principle the resulting tree need not have a preferred tip ("main" latest revision) – just various different revisions – but in practice one tip is generally identified as HEAD.
[src:subversion/version-control] When a new revision is based on HEAD, it is either identified as the new HEAD, or considered a new branch.
[src:subversion/version-control] This most often occurs when changes occur in multiple branches (most often two, but more are possible), which are then merged into a single branch incorporating both changes.
[src:subversion/version-control] If these changes overlap, it may be difficult or impossible to merge, and require manual intervention or rewriting.
[src:subversion/version-control] In the presence of merges, the resulting graph is no longer a tree, as nodes can have multiple parents, but is instead a rooted directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:subversion/version-control] The graph is acyclic since parents are always backwards in time, and rooted because there is an oldest version.
[src:subversion/version-control] Assuming there is a trunk, merges from branches can be considered as "external" to the tree – the changes in the branch are packaged up as a *patch,* which is applied to HEAD (of the trunk), creating a new revision without any explicit reference to the branch, and preserving the tree structure.
[src:subversion/version-control] Thus, while the actual relations between versions form a DAG, this can be considered a tree plus merges, and the trunk itself is a line.
[src:subversion/version-control] In distributed revision control, in the presence of multiple repositories these may be based on a single original version (a root of the tree), but there need not be an original root - instead there can be a separate root (oldest revision) for each repository.
[src:subversion/version-control] This can happen, for example, if two people start working on a project separately.
[src:subversion/version-control] Similarly, in the presence of multiple data sets (multiple projects) that exchange data or merge, there is no single root, though for simplicity one may think of one project as primary and the other as secondary, merged into the first with or without its own revision history.
[src:subversion/version-control] Engineering revision control developed from formalized processes based on tracking revisions of early blueprints or bluelines*"MIL-STD-100G: Department of Defense Standard Practice for Engineering Drawings" (PDF).
[src:subversion/version-control] This system of control implicitly allowed returning to an earlier state of the design, for cases in which an engineering dead-end was reached in the development of the design.
[src:subversion/version-control] A revision table was used to keep track of the changes made.
[src:subversion/version-control] Additionally, the modified areas of the drawing were highlighted using revision clouds.
[src:subversion/version-control] Version control is widespread in business and law.
[src:subversion/version-control] Indeed, "contract redline" and "legal blackline" are some of the earliest forms of revision control, and are still employed in business and law with varying degrees of sophistication.
[src:subversion/version-control] The most sophisticated techniques are beginning to be used for the electronic tracking of changes to CAD files (see product data management), supplanting the "manual" electronic implementation of traditional revision control.
[src:subversion/version-control] Game development often involves large binary files and teams working together across different disciplines.
[src:subversion/version-control] As a result, game studios use version control systems with good support for large binary files, file locking, and fast synchronization.
[src:subversion/version-control] Common tools include Perforce and several newer cloud-based systems.
[src:subversion/version-control] Traditional revision control systems use a centralized model where all the revision control functions take place on a shared server.
[src:subversion/version-control] If two developers try to change the same file at the same time, without some method of managing access the developers may end up overwriting each other's work.
[src:subversion/version-control] Centralized revision control systems solve this problem in one of two different "source management models": file locking and version merging.
[src:subversion/version-control] An operation is *atomic* if the system is left in a consistent state even if the operation is interrupted.
[src:subversion/version-control] The *commit* operation is usually the most critical in this sense.
[src:subversion/version-control] Commits tell the revision control system to make a group of changes final, and available to all users.
[src:subversion/version-control] Not all revision control systems have atomic commits; Concurrent Versions System lacks this feature.
[src:subversion/version-control] The simplest method of preventing "concurrent access" problems involves locking files so that only one developer at a time has write access to the central "repository" copies of those files.
[src:subversion/version-control] Once one developer "checks out" a file, others can read that file, but no one else may change that file until that developer "checks in" the updated version (or cancels the checkout).
[src:subversion/version-control] File locking has both merits and drawbacks.
[src:subversion/version-control] It can provide some protection against difficult merge conflicts when a user is making radical changes to many sections of a large file (or group of files).
[src:subversion/version-control] If the files are left exclusively locked for too long, other developers may be tempted to bypass the revision control software and change the files locally, forcing a difficult manual merge when the other changes are finally checked in.
[src:subversion/version-control] In a large organization, files can be left "checked out" and locked and forgotten about as developers move between projects - these tools may or may not make it easy to see who has a file checked out.
[src:subversion/version-control] Most version control systems allow multiple developers to edit the same file at the same time.
[src:subversion/version-control] The first developer to "check in" changes to the central repository always succeeds.
[src:subversion/version-control] The system may provide facilities to merge further changes into the central repository, and preserve the changes from the first developer when other developers check in.
[src:subversion/version-control] Merging two files can be a very delicate operation, and usually possible only if the data structure is simple, as in text files.
[src:subversion/version-control] The result of a merge of two image files might not result in an image file at all.
[src:subversion/version-control] The second developer checking in files will need to take care with the merge, to make sure that the changes are compatible and that the merge operation does not introduce its own logic errors within the files.
[src:subversion/version-control] These problems limit the availability of automatic or semi-automatic merge operations mainly to simple text-based documents, unless a specific merge plugin is available for the file types.
[src:subversion/version-control] The concept of a *reserved edit* can provide an optional means to explicitly lock a file for exclusive write access, even when a merging capability exists.
[src:subversion/version-control] Most revision control tools will use only one of these similar terms (baseline, label, tag) to refer to the action of identifying a snapshot ("label the project") or the record of the snapshot ("try it with baseline *X*").
[src:subversion/version-control] Typically only one of the terms *baseline*, *label*, or *tag* is used in documentation or discussion ; they can be considered synonyms.
[src:subversion/version-control] In most projects, some snapshots are more significant than others, such as those used to indicate published releases, branches, or milestones.
[src:subversion/version-control] When both the term *baseline* and either of *label* or *tag* are used together in the same context, *label* and *tag* usually refer to the mechanism within the tool of identifying or making the record of the snapshot, and *baseline* indicates the increased significance of any given label or tag.
[src:subversion/version-control] Most formal discussion of configuration management uses the term *baseline*.
[src:subversion/version-control] Distributed revision control systems (DRCS) take a peer-to-peer approach, as opposed to the client–server approach of centralized systems.
[src:subversion/version-control] Rather than a single, central repository on which clients synchronize, each peer's working copy of the codebase is a bona-fide repository.
[src:subversion/version-control] Distributed revision control conducts synchronization by exchanging patches (change-sets) from peer to peer.
[src:subversion/version-control] Rather, communication is only necessary when pushing or pulling changes to or from other peers.
[src:subversion/version-control] Following best practices is necessary to obtain the full benefits of version control.
[src:subversion/version-control] Best practice may vary by version control tool and the field to which version control is applied.
[src:subversion/version-control] Other software development best practices such as code review and automated regression testing may assist in the following of version control best practices.
[src:subversion/version-control] Costs and benefits will vary dependent upon the version control tool chosen and the field in which it is applied.
[src:subversion/version-control] This section speaks to the field of software development, where version control is widely applied.
[src:subversion/version-control] In addition to the costs of licensing the version control software, using version control requires time and effort.
[src:subversion/version-control] The concepts underlying version control must be understood and the technical particulars required to operate the version control software chosen must be learned.
[src:subversion/version-control] Version control best practices must be learned and integrated into the organization's existing software development practices.
[src:subversion/version-control] Management effort may be required to maintain the discipline needed to follow best practices in order to obtain useful benefit.
[src:subversion/version-control] A core benefit is the ability to keep history and revert changes, allowing the developer to easily undo changes.
[src:subversion/version-control] This gives the developer more opportunity to experiment, eliminating the fear of breaking existing code.
[src:subversion/version-control] Branching assists with deployment and release management.
[src:subversion/version-control] There can be damage mitigation, accountability, process and design improvement, and other benefits associated with the record keeping provided by version control, the tracking of who did what, when, why, and how.
[src:subversion/version-control] When bugs arise, knowing what was done when helps with damage mitigation and recovery by assisting in the identification of what problems exist, how long they have existed, and determining problem scope and solutions.
[src:subversion/version-control] Previous versions can be installed and tested to verify conclusions reached by examination of code and commit messages.
[src:subversion/version-control] Version control can greatly simplify debugging.
[src:subversion/version-control] The application of a test case to multiple versions can quickly identify the change which introduced a bug.
[src:subversion/version-control] The developer need not be familiar with the entire code base and can focus instead on the code that introduced the problem.
[src:subversion/version-control] Version control enhances collaboration in multiple ways.
[src:subversion/version-control] Since version control can identify conflicting changes, i.e. incompatible changes made to the same lines of code, there is less need for coordination among developers.
[src:subversion/version-control] The packaging of commits, branches, and all the associated commit messages and version labels, improves communication between developers, both in the moment and over time.
[src:subversion/version-control] Better communication, whether instant or deferred, can improve the code review process, the testing process, and other critical aspects of the software development process.
[src:subversion/version-control] Some of the more advanced revision-control tools offer many other facilities, allowing deeper integration with other tools and software-engineering processes.
[src:subversion/version-control] Plugins are often available for IDEs such as Oracle JDeveloper, IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse, Visual Studio, Delphi, NetBeans IDE, Xcode, and GNU Emacs (via vc.el).
[src:subversion/version-control] Advanced research prototypes generate appropriate commit messages.
[src:subversion/version-control] An approved revision of a document or source file to which subsequent changes can be made.
[src:subversion/version-control] A search for the author and revision that last modified a particular line.
[src:subversion/version-control] A set of files under version control may be *branched* or *forked* at a point in time so that, from that time forward, two copies of those files may develop at different speeds or in different ways independently of each other.
[src:subversion/version-control] A *change* (or *diff*, or *delta*) represents a specific modification to a document under version control.
[src:subversion/version-control] The granularity of the modification considered a change varies between version control systems.
[src:subversion/version-control] On many version control systems with atomic multi-change commits, a *change list* (or *CL*), *change set*, *update*, or *patch* identifies the set of *changes* made in a single commit.
[src:subversion/version-control] This can also represent a sequential view of the source code, allowing the examination of source as of any particular changelist ID.
[src:subversion/version-control] To *check out* (or *co*) is to create a local working copy from the repository.
[src:subversion/version-control] A user may specify a specific revision or obtain the latest.
[src:subversion/version-control] The term 'checkout' can also be used as a noun to describe the working copy.
[src:subversion/version-control] When a file has been checked out from a shared file server, it cannot be edited by other users.
[src:subversion/version-control] Think of it like a hotel, when you check out, you no longer have access to its amenities.
[src:subversion/version-control] In version control software, a changeset (also known as commit and revision) is a set of alterations packaged together, along with meta-information about the alterations.
[src:subversion/version-control] A changeset describes the exact differences between two successive versions in the version control system's repository of changes.
[src:subversion/version-control] Changesets are typically treated as an atomic unit, an indivisible set, by version control systems.
[src:subversion/version-control] To *commit* (*check in*, *ci* or, more rarely, *install*, *submit* or *record*) is to write or merge the changes made in the working copy back to the repository.
[src:subversion/version-control] A commit contains metadata, typically the author information and a commit message that describes the change.
[src:subversion/version-control] A short note, written by the developer, stored with the commit, which describes the commit.
[src:subversion/version-control] Ideally, it records why the modification was made, a description of the modification's effect or purpose, and non-obvious aspects of how the change works.
[src:subversion/version-control] A conflict occurs when different parties make changes to the same document, and the system is unable to reconcile the changes.
[src:subversion/version-control] A user must *resolve* the conflict by combining the changes, or by selecting one change in favour of the other.
[src:subversion/version-control] Most revision control software uses delta compression, which retains only the differences between successive versions of files.
[src:subversion/version-control] This allows for more efficient storage of many different versions of files.
[src:subversion/version-control] A stream in which some or all file versions are mirrors of the parent stream's versions.
[src:subversion/version-control] The process of merging changes made in the main *trunk* into a development (feature or team) branch.
[src:subversion/version-control] Also sometimes called *tip*, this refers to the most recent commit, either to the trunk or to a branch.
[src:subversion/version-control] The trunk and each branch have their own head, though HEAD is sometimes loosely used to refer to the trunk.
[src:subversion/version-control] Some revision control software uses Interleaved deltas, a method that allows storing the history of text based files in a more efficient way than by using Delta compression.
[src:subversion/version-control] When a developer *locks* a file, no one else can update that file until it is unlocked.
[src:subversion/version-control] Locking can be supported by the version control system, or via informal communications between developers (aka *social locking*).
[src:subversion/version-control] Similar to *trunk*, but there can be a mainline for each branch.
[src:subversion/version-control] A *merge* or *integration* is an operation in which two sets of changes are applied to a file or set of files.
[src:subversion/version-control] The act of copying file content from a less controlled location into a more controlled location.
[src:subversion/version-control] For example, from a user's workspace into a repository, or from a stream to its parent.
[src:subversion/version-control] Copy revisions from one repository into another.
[src:subversion/version-control] *Pull* is initiated by the receiving repository, while *push* is initiated by the source.
[src:subversion/version-control] *Fetch* is sometimes used as a synonym for *pull*, or to mean a *pull* followed by an *update*.
[src:subversion/version-control] Contributions to a source code repository that uses a distributed version control system are commonly made by means of a pull request, also known as a merge request.
[src:subversion/version-control] The contributor requests that the project maintainer *pull* the source code change, hence the name "pull request".
[src:subversion/version-control] The maintainer has to *merge* the pull request if the contribution should become part of the source base.
[src:subversion/version-control] The developer creates a pull request to notify maintainers of a new change; a comment thread is associated with each pull request.
[src:subversion/version-control] This allows for focused discussion of code changes.
[src:subversion/version-control] Submitted pull requests are visible to anyone with repository access.
[src:subversion/version-control] A pull request can be accepted or rejected by maintainers.
[src:subversion/version-control] Once the pull request is reviewed and approved, it is merged into the repository.
[src:subversion/version-control] Depending on the established workflow, the code may need to be tested before being included into official release.
[src:subversion/version-control] Therefore, some projects contain a special branch for merging untested pull requests.
[src:subversion/version-control] Other projects run an automated test suite on every pull request, using a continuous integration tool, and the reviewer checks that any new code has appropriate test coverage.
[src:subversion/version-control] In version control systems, a repository is a data structure that stores metadata for a set of files or directory structure.
[src:subversion/version-control] The act of user intervention to address a conflict between different changes to the same document.
[src:subversion/version-control] The process of merging different team branches into the main trunk of the versioning system.
[src:subversion/version-control] In SVK, a Revision is the state at a point in time of the entire tree in the repository.
[src:subversion/version-control] The act of making one file or folder available in multiple branches at the same time.
[src:subversion/version-control] When a shared file is changed in one branch, it is changed in other branches.
[src:subversion/version-control] A container for branched files that has a known relationship to other such containers.
[src:subversion/version-control] Streams form a hierarchy; each stream can inherit various properties (like versions, namespace, workflow rules, subscribers, etc.) from its parent stream.
[src:subversion/version-control] A *tag* or *label* refers to an important snapshot in time, consistent across many files.
[src:subversion/version-control] These files at that point may all be tagged with a user-friendly, meaningful name or revision number.
[src:subversion/version-control] An *update* (or *sync*, but *sync* can also mean a combined *push* and *pull*) merges changes made in the repository (by other people, for example) into the local *working copy*.
[src:subversion/version-control] *Update* is also the term used by some CM tools (CM+, PLS, SMS) for the change package concept (see *changelist*).
[src:subversion/version-control] The *working copy* is the local copy of files from a repository, at a specific time or revision.
[src:subversion/version-control] All work done to the files in a repository is initially done on a working copy, hence the name.
